body:
[Playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2021&gist=4edfdb91cdf2df5f6e7a17bb82da0fb9)
 
 It's rather a suggestion than a bug.

Have this code:

```rust
use std::ffi::CString;

fn main() {
    let pointer = CString::new("Hello world!").unwrap().as_ptr();
    unsafe {
        println!("{:?}", *pointer as u8 as char);
    }
}
```
Rust reports the warning `rustc(temporary_cstring_as_ptr)` during build. The detail is ``this `CString` is deallocated at the end of the statement, bind it to a variable to extend its lifetime`` which is expected :ok: .
If you run the code, a "random" character will be printed and that's of course unexpected. A solution is an assignment of the string into a standalone variable as explained [here](https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/ffi/struct.CString.html#method.as_ptr).

---
Have the same code, but this time it uses `String` instead of `CString`:
```rust
fn main() {
    let pointer = String::from("Hello world!").as_ptr();

    unsafe {
        println!("{:?}", *pointer as char);
    }
}
```

**I expected to see this happen:**
* I should get similar kind of warning as in case of `CString`, because also in this case the pointer is dangling and if you run the code, a random character will be printed. A solution is the same as for `CString`

**Instead, this happened:**
* Rust doesn't warn

